  • Is the plotPCA plot based on all genes in the dataset? How can we change how many genes are used for the PCA analysis? Does this significantly change the plot? (HINT: check the documentation for the plotPCA function.)
  • Do the samples appear to be separated based on the type of treatment applied?
  • What problems can you see with the metadata?
  • Can you label the identify of each sample? Look for help on geom_textif you haven’t used it before
vsd <- vst(dds)
using 'avgTxLength' from assays(dds), correcting for library size
plotPCA(vsd,intgroup="Treated")

Asking for the help on plotPCA suggests two possibilities. Pick the one that mentions DESeq2. The plotPCA function has a ntop argument which is set to 500; in other words only 500 genes are used to make the plot. It does not seem to make a huge difference how many genes are used.

?plotPCA
plotPCA(vsd, intgroup="Treated",ntop=1000)
plotPCA(vsd, intgroup="Treated",ntop=5000)

  • Yes the samples appear to separate based on treatment

  • There are more colours indicating condition than we would expect. There are typos in the values in this column that we need to fix

plotPCA(vsd,intgroup="condition")

  • Using the geom_text function requires a label aesthetic to be set. We can make this the Name column in pca_data for example.
library(ggplot2)
pca_data <- plotPCA(vsd,intgroup="Treated",returnData = TRUE) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(Run = name) %>% 
  left_join(sampleInfo)
Joining, by = c("Treated", "Run")
  ggplot(pca_data,aes(x = PC1, y = PC2,col=Treated,label=Name)) + geom_point() + geom_text()

  • Write the entire results table to a csv file
  • Sort the differential expression results according to adjusted p-value
  • Restrict the data to genes with adjusted p-value less than 0.05 and log2FoldChange > 1 or < -1
